  "How many independent variables should a well-designed experiment have?": "",
  "As many as possible": "",
  "Exactly one": "",
  "At least three": "",
  "Exactly two": "",
  "A well-designed experiment should test only one independent variable at a time. Testing more than one makes it impossible to determine which variable caused the observed changes in the dependent variable.": "",
  "The dependent variable is also known as which of the following?": "",
  "The manipulated variable": "",
  "The dependent variable is also called the responding variable because it responds to changes in the independent variable. Similarly, the independent variable is sometimes called the manipulated variable.": "",
  "Which phrase best helps identify the independent variable in an experiment?": "",
  "What I observe at the end of the experiment": "",
  "What I keep the same throughout the experiment": "",
  "What I change on purpose during the experiment": "",
  "What I record in the data table after testing": "",
  "The independent variable is what the experimenter changes on purpose. Asking 'What am I changing?' helps you identify it. The dependent variable answers 'What am I measuring?' in response to that change.": "",
  "If you wanted to test how fertilizer affects tomato plant height, what would you measure?": "",
  "The amount of fertilizer added to each plant": "",
  "The height of the tomato plants over time": "",
  "The type of soil used in each planting pot": "",
  "The brand of fertilizer purchased at the store": "",
  "You would measure the height of the tomato plants because that is the dependent variable — the outcome that responds to the amount of fertilizer (independent variable) you add.": "",
  "In the hypothesis 'If the temperature increases, then ice will melt faster,' which is the independent variable?": "",
  "The speed of ice melting": "",
  "The size of the ice cubes": "",
  "The temperature level": "",
  "The type of container used": "",
  "In an if-then hypothesis, the 'if' part usually contains the independent variable (temperature) and the 'then' part contains the dependent variable (melting speed). Temperature is what the scientist changes.": "",
  "What is an independent variable?": "",
  "The factor that the scientist deliberately changes to test its effect on outcomes": "",
  "The factor that changes in response to something else during the experiment": "",
  "A factor that must remain the same throughout all trials of the experiment": "",
  "A factor that is only important during the conclusion of the experiment": "",
  "An independent variable is the factor that the experimenter intentionally changes or manipulates to observe its effect on another variable. It is independent because it does not depend on other variables in the experiment.": "",
  "What is a dependent variable?": "",
  "The factor that the scientist intentionally changes during the experiment": "",
  "The factor that is measured or observed as a result of changes made": "",
  "A factor that stays constant and unchanged throughout the experiment": "",
  "A factor that has no relationship to any other variables being tested": "",
  "A dependent variable is the factor that is measured or observed during an experiment. It is called dependent because its value depends on changes made to the independent variable.": "",
  "What does 'manipulated variable' mean?": "",
  "A variable that is measured at the end of an experiment to collect data": "",
  "Another name for the independent variable that a scientist controls": "",
  "A variable that must be kept constant throughout each trial run": "",
  "A variable that randomly changes without the scientist controlling it": "",
  "The manipulated variable is another name for the independent variable. It is called 'manipulated' because the scientist deliberately manipulates (changes) it to observe its effect on the dependent variable.": "",
  "What does 'responding variable' mean?": "",
  "The variable that the experimenter chooses to change on purpose": "",
  "Another name for the dependent variable that changes in response": "",
  "A variable that remains unchanged during all parts of a test": "",
  "The answer given by a participant in a scientific survey study": "",
  "The responding variable is another name for the dependent variable. It is called 'responding' because it responds to or changes because of the independent variable.": "",
  "What is a controlled variable (constant)?": "",
  "A factor that is deliberately changed by the experimenter to test a hypothesis": "",
  "A factor that is kept the same in every trial to ensure a fair test": "",
  "A factor that the experimenter measures to determine the experiment's outcome": "",
  "A factor that varies randomly during the experiment without being planned": "",
  "A controlled variable (or constant) is a factor kept the same in every trial of an experiment. This ensures that any change in the dependent variable is caused only by the independent variable, making the test fair.": "",
  "What does 'cause and effect' mean in an experiment?": "",
  "Changing one variable (the cause) produces a measurable change in another (the effect)": "",
  "Two variables that happen at the same time but have no actual connection to each other": "",
  "The process of keeping all variables constant so that nothing in the experiment changes": "",
  "The step in the scientific method where the scientist writes a detailed conclusion": "",
  "Cause and effect means that changing one factor (the cause, or independent variable) directly produces a change in another factor (the effect, or dependent variable). Experiments are designed to establish cause-and-effect relationships.": "",
  "What does it mean to 'isolate a variable'?": "",
  "To test only one independent variable while keeping all others constant": "",
  "To remove a variable completely so it plays no role in the experiment": "",
  "To change multiple variables at the same time to speed up the testing": "",
  "To repeat the same experiment without changing any variables at all": "",
  "Isolating a variable means testing only one factor at a time while keeping everything else constant. This allows the scientist to determine whether the independent variable truly caused the observed change.": "",
  "What is a confounding variable?": "",
  "A variable that is plotted on the y-axis of the final data graph": "",
  "An uncontrolled factor that may affect the results and lead to incorrect conclusions": "",
  "The dependent variable that responds to changes made by the scientist": "",
  "A variable that is deliberately changed by the scientist during the test": "",
  "A confounding variable is an uncontrolled factor that changes along with the independent variable and may influence the results. If not controlled, it makes it impossible to know which factor truly caused the observed effect.": "",
  "What does 'operationally define a variable' mean?": "",
  "To describe exactly how a variable will be measured or changed in the experiment": "",
  "To decide which variable is the most important one to study in the test": "",
  "To remove a variable from the experiment because it is not needed at all": "",
  "To name a variable using a scientific term from a physics textbook source": "",
  "Operationally defining a variable means stating precisely how it will be measured or manipulated. For example, instead of saying 'plant growth,' you specify 'height in centimeters measured from soil to tip.'": "",
  "What is a fair test in science?": "",
  "An experiment where only the independent variable changes and all others stay the same": "",
  "An experiment where every variable is changed at the same time for efficiency": "",
  "An experiment that produces results matching exactly what the scientist predicted": "",
  "An experiment where the scientist does not know which variable is being tested": "",
  "A fair test is an experiment where only the independent variable is changed while all other variables (constants) are kept the same. This ensures that any observed changes in the dependent variable are due to the independent variable.": "",
  "A student wants to test whether the type of surface affects how far a toy car rolls. She tests the car on carpet, tile, and wood. What is the independent variable?": "",
  "The distance the toy car rolls on each surface": "",
  "The type of surface the car rolls across": "",
  "The weight of the toy car being tested here": "",
  "The height of the ramp used to launch the car": "",
  "The type of surface (carpet, tile, wood) is the independent variable because the student deliberately chooses to change it. The distance the car rolls is the dependent variable that she measures.": "",
  "A scientist tests whether the color of light affects how fast a plant grows. She uses red, blue, and white lights. What is the dependent variable in this experiment?": "",
  "The color of the light used on each plant": "",
  "The rate at which the plants grow under each light": "",
  "The type of soil placed in each plant pot": "",
  "The amount of water given to each plant daily": "",
  "The growth rate of the plants is the dependent variable because it is what the scientist measures to see the effect of different light colors. The light color is the independent variable.": "",
  "A student tests how the mass of a ball affects its bounce height. He keeps the drop height, surface type, and ball size the same. What are these kept-same factors called?": "",
  "They are the independent variables in this experiment": "",
  "They are the dependent variables being measured here": "",
  "They are confounding variables affecting the results": "",
  "They are controlled variables (constants) in this test": "",
  "Drop height, surface type, and ball size are controlled variables (constants). They must be kept the same so the student knows that any change in bounce height is caused only by the mass of the ball.": "",
  "Two students design an experiment to test how water temperature affects goldfish breathing rate. Student A changes only the water temperature. Student B changes both the temperature and the amount of food. Whose experiment is better designed?": "",
  "Student B, because changing more variables gives more useful data points": "",
  "Neither student, because goldfish experiments are not valid for science": "",
  "Student A, because only one variable is changed so results are easier to interpret": "",
  "Both students, because changing any number of variables is equally acceptable": "",
  "Student A's experiment is better designed because only one independent variable (temperature) is changed. Student B's design is flawed because changing both temperature and food makes it impossible to tell which factor caused any change in breathing rate.": "",
  "A student hypothesizes: 'If I increase the angle of a ramp, then a marble will roll faster.' She measures the marble's speed at the bottom for ramp angles of 10°, 20°, 30°, and 40°. What should she graph on the x-axis?": "",
  "The speed of the marble at the bottom of the ramp": "",
  "The number of trials performed at each angle": "",
  "The angle of the ramp in degrees for each trial": "",
  "The time it takes the marble to reach the bottom": "",
  "The ramp angle is the independent variable (what the student changes on purpose), so it goes on the x-axis. The marble's speed is the dependent variable (what she measures) and goes on the y-axis.": "",
  "A student notices that students who eat breakfast score higher on tests. Can she conclude that eating breakfast causes higher test scores? Why or why not?": "",
  "Yes, because the data clearly shows that breakfast causes better test performance": "",
  "No, because this is an observation, not a controlled experiment, so other factors could explain it": "",
  "Yes, because whenever two things happen together one must always cause the other": "",
  "No, because test scores can never be influenced by any outside factors at all": "",
  "This is an observation, not a controlled experiment. Confounding variables (sleep habits, study time, stress) could also explain higher scores. Only a controlled experiment isolating breakfast as the independent variable could establish cause and effect.": "",
  "A student tests whether the brand of battery affects how long a flashlight stays on. She uses three different brands but accidentally uses different flashlights for each brand. What is wrong with her experiment?": "",
  "She should have used only one brand of battery for the entire test run": "",
  "She introduced a confounding variable by not keeping the flashlight the same": "",
  "She should have measured the brightness of the light instead of the duration": "",
  "Nothing is wrong; using different flashlights makes the experiment more thorough": "",
  "Using different flashlights introduces a confounding variable — differences in flashlight efficiency could affect how long they stay on. She should use the same flashlight for all brands to keep it as a controlled variable.": "",
  "A student tests how the length of a pendulum affects its swing time. She changes the string length but also changes the weight at the bottom each time. Can she determine what caused differences in swing time?": "",
